[2] Newcastle disease, Romania (Covasna)
Date: 4 Nov 2007
Source: OIE WAHID Disease Information 2007; 20(45) [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=weekly_report_index&admin=0>


Information received on (and dated) 2 Nov 2007 from Dr Stefan Nicolae,
directeur general, Direction Generale, Autorite Nationale Sanitaire
Veterinaire pour la Securite des Aliments (ANSVSA), Bucuresti , Romania

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Start date: 17 Oct 2007
Date of confirmation of event: 29 Oct 10 2007
Date submitted to OIE: 2 Nov 2007
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 16 Aug 2007
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Newcastle disease virus
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (advanced)
Report pertains to: entire country

New outbreaks
Outbreak 1: Comandau, Covasna
Date of start of outbreak: 17 Oct 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Species: birds
Susceptible 26
Cases 1
Deaths 1
Destroyed 25
Slaughtered 0
Affected population backyard poultry
Summary of outbreaks: total outbreaks: 1

Outbreak statistics
Species: birds
Apparent morbidity rate 4 per cent
Apparent mortality rate 4 per cent
Apparent case fatality rate 100 per cent
Proportion susceptible removed* 100 per cent
* Removed from the susceptible population either through death, destruction
or slaughter

Epidemiology: source of infection - unknown or inconclusive

Laboratory name and type: Institute for Diagnosis and Animal Health
(National laboratory)
Species: birds
Test: reverse transcription - polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR)
Test date: 29 Oct 2007
Result: positive

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Reythemo is one of the 4 prefectures of Crete and can be seen at
<http://66.29.86.75/crete-maps/Crete-eot.png> or at the OIE WAHID reference
above. These OIE WAHID references almost always contains a map of the
outbreak location. Likewise, the location of the outbreak in Romania in
Covasna County can be seen at OIE WAHID or at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covasna_County>.

Although there appears to be little relationship geographically between
these 2 outbreaks, they did occur within a week of each other with starting
dates of 23 Oct 2007 in Greece and 17 Oct 2007 in Romania. It would be
interesting if a cooperative outbreak investigation implicates a commercial
linkage or intensive surveillance in wildlife shows some risk that accounts
for an admittedly somewhat tenuous association in time but disparate
location in space. In the end, these outbreaks may have nothing to do with
each other, but making progress in identifying sources of outbreaks for
poultry diseases should be a priority. - Mod.PC]
